<h2>HVAC Systems in West Virginia</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>West Virginia's humid continental climate presents unique challenges and opportunities for HVAC system design and operation. The state experiences four distinct seasons with significant temperature variations, ranging from average winter lows in the teens to summer highs in the 80s Fahrenheit. Humidity levels remain relatively high throughout the year, particularly during summer months, requiring HVAC systems capable of effective dehumidification alongside temperature control.</p>

<p>The mountainous terrain creates microclimates throughout the state, with elevation changes affecting both temperature and precipitation patterns. Higher elevations in the Alleghenies experience longer, colder winters and shorter cooling seasons, while river valleys and lower elevations face more extended periods requiring air conditioning. This geographic diversity means HVAC system sizing and efficiency requirements can vary significantly even within the same county.</p>

<p>Heat pump systems are particularly well-suited to West Virginia's climate, as they provide both heating and cooling capabilities while operating efficiently in the state's moderate temperature ranges. Modern cold-climate heat pumps can effectively heat homes even when outdoor temperatures drop below freezing, making them an excellent alternative to traditional electric resistance heating or propane systems common in rural areas. The state's relatively stable shoulder seasons also provide opportunities for natural ventilation and reduced HVAC runtime, further improving system efficiency and reducing energy costs.</p>

